{"id":"2107.03793","submitter":"Fr\\'ed\\'eric Meunier","authors":"H\\'el\\`ene Langlois, Fr\\'ed\\'eric Meunier, Romeo Rizzi and St\\'ephane\n  Vialette","title":"Algorithmic aspects of quasi-kernels","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.DM math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In a digraph, a quasi-kernel is a subset of vertices that is independent and\nsuch that every vertex can reach some vertex in that set via a directed path of\nlength at most two. Whereas Chv\\'atal and Lov\\'asz proved in 1974 that every\ndigraph has a quasi-kernel, very little is known so far about the complexity of\nfinding small quasi-kernels. In 1976 Erd\\H{o}s and Sz\\'ekely conjectured that\nevery sink-free digraph $D = (V, A)$ has a quasi-kernel of size at most\n$|V|/2$. Obviously, if $D$ has two disjoint quasi-kernels then it has a\nquasi-kernel of size at most $|V|/2$, and in 2001 Gutin, Koh, Tay and Yeo\nconjectured that every sink-free digraph has two disjoint quasi-kernels. Yet,\nthey constructed in 2004 a counterexample, thereby disproving this stronger\nconjecture. We shall show that, not only sink-free digraphs occasionally fail\nto contain two disjoint quasi-kernels, but it is computationally hard to\ndistinguish those that do from those that do not. We also prove that the\nproblem of computing a small quasi-kernel is polynomial time solvable for\norientations of trees but is computationally hard in most other cases (and in\nparticular for restricted acyclic digraphs).\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 8 Jul 2021 12:07:48 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-07-09"}
